inn1.comm: over the wicket and he pushes that one across the lefthander
a push in front of point - hesitation after the first, but it's Panesar out there and they decide on a second run
swings that one back into the lefthander at the last minute, but not near enough the stumps to be of interest and that's well left alone
overstepped for that no-ball and the batsman jabs the ball down behind point for an easy single
a good leave to one which cut back in
up there on a good length and Astle squeezes the ball into short midwicket and looks for a run to get off the mark, but there wasn't one on
Astle off the mark this time with an easily dinked flick off the legs
short and straight and that's defended down off the back foot
left alone outside off stump
ooh, beauty from Anderson, just failing to take the outside edge as the batsman prodded off the back foot, the bat away from his body

he's gone this time! Anderson softened him up with the previous delivery and Astle jabs once more at this one which is pitched up, but this time a straightforward edge flies into the hands of Collingwood at second slip who makes no mistake. Good bowling from Anderson, poor shot from Astle
defended down first up
over the wicket to the lefthander who shoulders arms
squares up to that one and there's a sort-of ooh as the ball flies through... but way away the edge in fact
another overstep from Lewis, just trying to find his rhythm here
good line and length from Lewis, forcing the batsman to defend solidly on the front foot
good carry this time on a fresh Adelaide pitch, Fleming shouldering arms early
in the same area, not near enough to provoke a shot - Fleming leaves that one alone
ooh! Good stuff from Lewis there, nipping that one just away from the lefthander on a good length, but it's good judgement from Fleming, too, who chooses to leave
rushed past the outside edge
defended this time
too straight and that's New Zealand's first boundary, square of the wicket with a nicely timed wristy pull, right over the ball
Anderson overcompensates and that swings away down off
the feisty youngster Nixon leads the appeals behind the stumps as that one just nips back in, Fulton deceived, expecting the awayswinger. But the ball wasn't doing enough to come back in
on a good length, angling in at the righthander, who defends solidly on the front foot
banged in, the ball doesn't get up, but it's on a good length, the batsman defends down on the back foot and they decide to "Wait on".
flicked down the leg-side, a good take from Nixon, diving and then rolling away to his right, but the umpire decides it's not out and that's a good call; it was brushing the thigh pad
loose swish to a very wide one
well-judged leave as that one rushes through
defended forward
left alone as that one swings a touch outside off
another leave
defended forward this time - tidy enough over from Lewis
defended forward
hint of away swing and the batsman chooses to leave
left alone once more
more leaving as that one bends right away from the righthander who goes back on to the balls of his toes and leaves it
a better length and Fulton's in two minds - he chooses in the end to fend at the ball away from his body, just to say getting on to his back foot, and he misses the ball
an edge through fine gully ... just where Flintoff had removed the man earlier this over
defended on the front foot into cover
defended forward
Fleming again leaves that one, this angled right across him
worked off the toes to square
creeps right over that one to defend forward
flashes right over the ball this time, his feet caught in the crease - another good over from England
unconvincing smack at that one, trying to drive through mid-off, but getting an inside edge which sends the ball forward towards mid-on
well bowled, defending that one on the front foot

good running from New Zealand there - they'll take anything they can get right now - as the ball drops down off Fulton's under edge. Nixon rushes forward to kick the ball at the stumps, misses, and Fleming makes his ground easily
leg-stump half-volley and Fleming rushes at that one, trying to work it through midwicket, but it clatters into his pads. Missed out, there
a lesser-spotted four! Spotted! Another loose delivery, on the off-side this time, is driven through cover and just bobbles over the rope
left alone outside off stump

a huge appeal for one which was outside the line - two arms going back for Lewis in that one, Dominic Cork-style of appeal, but the batsman was far enough forward and the batsman was probably just outside the line of off stump as well
worked just behind square
jabs his hands down on that one and the ball goes to midwicket
pushed up there and it's defended on the front foot
full again and defended once more
lovely shot, chipped easily into the leg-side and the ball flies away
tries a similar shot, but misses it and the ball flies through to Nixon. Fleming takes a few seconds to reflect on that shot and to stare at Anderson
Anderson snatches at a return bump-ball, misses, but pretends to shy at Fleming's stumps. Fleming's too wise a customer to be fooled and looks for the quick single, but it's not on
worked well into the midwicket
crashed off the back foot through cover and that's the second four this over for New Zealand, who are picking up a bit of momentum here
good reply from Anderson, nipping that one in at the righthander
six! Splendid shot, whipped off the toes and that goes high and safe and over midwicket. Good stuff from Fleming, well picked up early
a better line from Lewis, tempting Fleming to squirt that up to point and it bounces short
ooh, a top edge off a late cut drops short in front of the slips
Fleming looks to dink that forcefully off his toes in front of square, but readjusts at the last minute, dropping soft hands onto the shot
ooh, that one's straight and raps him on the pads, and there's a big shout from Lewis but it's too short and would have gone a good few inches (or many centimetres, if you like) over
worked into midwicket for an easy single
over the wicket and that's left alone outside off&
driven to short mid-off and there's a fumble, then a "Good recovery, Jim", from Anderson
angled across the left hander at 88mph (141kmh)
goes hard at that one, but doesn't quite time it and that's lashed out to point where it's picked up neatly
worked into the covers where Bell snaps it up

a huge shout and that's gone! Flintoff has struck first over with a 90mph (145kmh) which attacks along an off-stump line and takes a fine edge through to Nixon, Fleming's feet trapped in the crease. Big blow for New Zealand, just as their captain was starting to get going
oh, good line from Lewis and that's well left alone
nudged into midwicket and that's a quick single
the batsman comes forward to press a text-book defensive into the covers
straight and that's defended off the back foot
worked down off the back foot
on a good length and defended
short and fast and the batsman rushes at it, but misses
tucked off the toes into midwicket and that's "Well done, Mal" as Loye throws the ball back into Nixon
left alone as that one swings a touch away outside off
good rhythm from Flintoff and again that hits a good area
just strays onto leg and that's caressed to square where Ed Joyce does the honours
on a good length and that's defended once more
driven into the covers
flashes a cut at that one, doesn't get hold of it, and gets an edge into the ground, but safe, his bottom hand flying up off the bat
tidily defended
worked off the toes in front of midwicket for a quick single, well taken
attempts a cross-batted swipe at one which pitches on off, misses, and it clatters into him
tries to pull this one and that's a bit of a desperate swipe once more, aiming for midwicket, finding the inside edge
like the class geek, he takes a big swat at that one, misses and that rushes through to Nixon who "Oohs" at the fact it missed the outside edge
defended on the back foot, Flintoff scoops the ball on the follow through and mock-shies at the stumps
crashed into the pads
worked into the covers
defended off the back foot this time
straight, defended off the back foot and a trio of fielders rush to pick up the ball - up-and-at-'em body language for England, which has been rare this tour
guided easily to square
width there and that's a scorching boundary for Taylor, clattering that away through cover with fast hands and good power. More of those would be great for this game
left alone outside off
pushed right up there and defended into midwicket
defended off the back foot with a push behind point and New Zealand decide the best option is "Waiting"
worked to point this time
tickled slowly to midwicket
a huge inside edge but Nixon still appeals for LBW and Flintoff joins him in a guilty half-appeal. You could hear they didn't really mean it
quick single... turned into two as Anderson at mid-on pretends to throw down the stumps under arm... but he missed the ball completely
quick single on the off-side
Fulton stands tall and drives that to mid-off but Panesar fluffs that one and allows the single
cannons into the bat and dinks down to gully
lofted on-drive just clears the rope. Neat shot

ah, gone this time. Floated just outside off stump, a slower ball, offspinner and the batsman played too early, spooning a simple catch to Collingwood at backward point. Good response from Lewis but New Zealand's sliver of momentum has been punctured again. Much rests on Taylor's shoulders now
a play and a miss first up
solid defence this time
on a good length and there's a gravel-voiced decision to "Waaait"
nudged away off the front foot in front of midwicket, nicely timed and Joyce engages in a relay throw from the short boundary, bless him
bouncer, easily ducked under
fuller, straight again and the batsman defends that one on the front foot
driven straight to point
steered off the hips behind square and that's some nice running there from New Zealand, earning the two thanks to a quick first one and some good judgement
unconvincing drive to mid-on, certainly not with the full face of the bat
defended forward
tidy start and that's driven to mid-off
sign of attacking intent to one which has width outside off and that's clattered behind point. Taylor playing with unusual restraint here, but that's sensible given the situation
worked to square

huge shout and plumb, McMillan playing all round one which angles back in ever-so-slightly. That would have taken middle about halfway up the stump. Collingwood strikes in his first over, good decision from Flintoff to bring him on
on the money and that's defended first up
more defence, on the front foot again
flashed a loose one hard at point, but it bounces well short and that's picked up well
strays on leg and that crashes into the pad as the batsman bends over
short, a touch of width, worked off the back foot into cover
defended forward
defended forward
worked off the hips to square and there's a quick single
offers a straight bat to that defensive shot on the front foot
outside edge flies down and through the vacant slip area
defended to mid-off
defended on the back foot this time
driven out to cover for an easy single
left alone as that one angles across him
worked behind square
on the money but that's worked out well into the leg-side
on the button, that's defended and is Nixon happy with that? "Yes, pal."

Panesar strikes! Good take at slip, snapped to his right, with Taylor trying to stroke that through cover, reaching for the ball. Monty's the fourth England bowler to take a wicket in his first over and there's a mire with New Zealand's name on it
worked off the legs into midwicket for a quick single
half-question, tellingly from Panesar only, for one which pitched outside the line
short and worked off the back foot behind point
driven to mid-on
driven again to mid-on
dabbed down off the back foot
driven to mid-on this time
byes from one which shoots past Nixon, too far for him to grab
defended forward
an attacking shot, yes it really was, rushed out to point
creeps forward to defend right over that one
played square off the hips
defended forward, tidy ball
worked behind square through the 45
worked to square
worked off his back foot
short and there's a backfoot drive through the covers
defended forward
pushed up there and driven to mid-off
driven out to the cover boundary
defended
worked behind square
defended forward this time
more defence, coming forward
dinked out to mid-off and New Zealand take the single
eased into the covers
ouch, Flintoff's hurt, diving for that one, his knee just jarring as it digs into the turf and he does an involuntary somersault. But he's up and stepping gingerly back onto the pitch
defended forward
slower ball (64.5mph/106kmh) and that's on the money and so defended
confidently driven through cover and there are huge cheers from a boundary-starved crowd
worked into midwicket and Nixon wants the boys to "lift it, here"
eased into the covers this time
stops on the shot, defending it into short midwicket
straight and there's a throaty yelp from Panesar for a sweep, but it's turned down - hitting the line outside off stump
defended
worked to square where Plunkett, on for Lewis, throws back
defended on the money
good running, the batsmen just making their ground for two after that's worked into a gap on the on-side
good delivery, better line, just to say going across the left hander who rushes at it and misses
driven at Bell in at shortish extra cover and that clatters into him as he fails to get hands on it, bobbling nastily into his wrists, and the batsmen manage a single
"Waiting" they decide as the batsman walks forward in defence
steps forward and looks to attack... but stands straight and defends forward into the covers
pushed up there and that's driven to cover
on the money and that's worked into short midwicket
half-hearted appeal as that crashes into the pads off an attempted sweep
worked in front of square
good sweep shot for one, Dalrymple coming round quickly to field
worked to mid-on into space there for an easy single
played into the gap in front of cover for a quick single
driven through the covers, Strauss diving over the ball
played into space on the on-side
worked off the hips to square
played out to the cover boundary where Joyce does well to race round. That's New Zealand's hundred
the ball spits a tad off just short of a length and that's defended down off the back foot
inside edge and there's an easy single with the man deep on the leg-side
defended down and Panesar does some tidy work to pick up the return
Strauss the guilty party - throwing the ball where a run-out wasn't really on and there's an overthrow
another shy, this time from mid-off, but there's no second run on this time
tucked well off the hips into space at midwicket
steered into the covers this time
worked to the man at backward square leg who picks it up easily
hostile start fizzing that one past the outside edge
huge shout for one which nips back in off the seam but that's not out, just outside the line of off stump
comes down the track and such is the effort of trying to thwack that through midwicket that he slips on the turf
worked into midwicket
down the pitch and ... defends
defended on the front foot and that's another one in the maiden column
loose one first up, floating down leg but misconnected
defended forward with a firm prod
pitches outside off and the batsman walks over to work it into the leg-side
bends that one down and that one is nurdled behind leg
the strike's rotated again, this time with a push off the back foot behind point
attempted sweep to a leg-side wide and Nixon whips off the bails more as a statement of intent than anything
defended this time
worked off the back foot into the covers
round the wicket and there's a hint of reverse swing from Flintoff, the batsman flashing at it, squaring up to that one on the back foot
eased into the covers
slinks that one down the channel outside off
outside off but that's wide, just going away from the left hander
wide outside off again but not wide enough to be a wide
opens the face and steers that one down to third man, good shot
worked into the covers this time
picked off the toes and worked into short midwicket
worked into the covers
oops, very wide down off
defended this time
defended again
worked off the legs to square
angles that one in at the left hander and the ball drifts away at the last second with a touch of reverse
a good length and that's defended off the back foot just outside off
worked to point off the back foot
strays down leg and that's worked to fine leg, great running, rushing back for two
on a good length, good line too - on off - and that's defended forward
yorker, well dug out
drags that a touch short and that's worked out in front of square
a big shot out of the locker clears the boundary. A six! Yes! Lovely aerial straight drive. Is this the start of some hitting out? Let's hope so
more attacking, hit flat at Joyce out in the deep at midwicket. He did well to get some body on it, the ball crashing into him on the bounce
driven to long-off and there's some good running there
on leg and that's tucked away square
dinked to point
just strays onto leg and that's worked to square
gives it a touch of width on off and that's driven to mid-off
reverse sweep goes very fine but it's a slow outfield and cut off. That's his fourth one-day fifty, a good innings in the circumstances
full bunger, swept to square for just the single
defended forward this time
short and rises up at the right hander who has time and room to defend that down off the back foot
slower ball, cutting in at the right hander who tries to work it behind point but doesn't really get hold of it
worked off the back foot into the covers
big pull shot bunted from outside off in front of midwicket
tries to aerial drive that, gets a huge outside edge just bouncing off Nixon's knee
could be trouble... ah, but thrown to the wrong end from midwicket
on leg and that's eased out along the ground into midwicket
comes down and tries a huge aerial drive into the off-side, but that goes inside out and safe, landing five metres inside the boundary
reverse swept through point to bring up the 150. Nobody in the deep out there
Panesar hopping in the appeal there, but there was no chance of that being LBW, he was a long way outside
shuffled into the huge space on the on-side
dabbed into the leg-side this time
the batsman comes early, but has to readjust, moving on to his back foot and leaning out to smack a short and wide one down off through cover
straight-driven but not timed properly, nevertheless the batsmen manage to squeeze out two runs
waited and stuns that off the back foot just in front of mid-on, where the batsmen race through for a well-taken single
wide and that's bunted from outside off to mid-on; more good running for the two
up there, slow yorker and that's dug out
rushed to the man at square who picks it up and that's "Good Mal, good Mal"
hit to square again
reverse sweep and there's a hopeful call from Panesar and Nixon. Leg byes are called, so it must be quite close
"Catch it!" is the cry but the ball plops just short of midwicket
hundred partnership with that pull, down on one knee and rocketed way over the boundary boards
more "Catch it" cries as that one lands over Flintoff's head and pitches just short of the midwicket boundary
full toss flatbatted straight and that heads in the direction of long-off
driven straight this time
full, dug out from off stump and driven to mid-on
speared up there again but that's driven out to long-off this time where Plunkett does the work
rushes an attempted drive at that but a huge edge flies straight behind the keeper and on to the boundary despite Panesar's best diving effort
ooh, good shot from Oram, splitting the fielders out on the midwicket boundary. There wasn't much room for him to swing his arms but he did ever so well to work it out and on to the ropes
driven off the back foot into the covers where Panesar does well to scramble over the ball and kill it
"Hoooooooooooooow?" asks Flintoff as Oram shuffles well across his crease and tries to take the ball from outside off through midwicket... but that hit him well outside the line of off stump

bowled him! Cleans up McCullum with one which takes a big inside edge and crashes right onto the stumps. So McCullum made 30, but they weren't comfortable runs by any stretch. Nevertheless he and Oram's stand has been invaluable in turning round this innings

round the wicket to the lefthander who scamrbles out a run immediately, dinking the ball down and running through. Flintoff did well to pick up, turn and knock down the non-striker's end stumps, but he'd made his ground
dug out and driven out to long off
full toss but the batsman fails to capitalise, as it's worked into the covers
way outside off and the batsman looks to swat it to cover, but he misses it completely

oops, Flintoff misjudged that ski-er, running round from wide mid-on. It's a hard one, but quite a comical drop actually when he dived over it, losing it in the sun. Michael Atherton is busy saying: "He's a safe pair of hands..." as he shells it. Ah
gone this time. The let-off didn't prove costly, Oram snapped up just behind square leg
defended forward
dug out to extra cover
bouncer, ducked under
moves backward to give himself room to cut, makes a complete hash of it, and is lucky that Flintoff's full delivery pitches just outside off
tight bowling from Flintoff again, straight and full, Vettori looking to give himself room
well bowled, following Franklin who was creeping away from his stumps and is forced to prod down a defence on the back foot in the end

good catch from Nixon, athletic, and going away to his left to pouch the thick edge. Full length again from Flintoff and the batsman swishes at that one, backing away to give himself room on the off-side
inside edge and Bond has no clue where the ball's gone... it went through his legs and behind square
yorker and Flintoff ends his spell perfectly, picking up his fourth wicket with a darting full delivery. That's 4 for 21 for him from his ten overs, top bowling
wide, full toss and Cricinfo shout "Village" in unison, the batsman making no mistake in bunting that out in front of point
wide down off, though that's a close call, and Anderson's not chuffed, hunching his sleeves up a la Steve Harmison as he walks back to his mark
sliced away behind point where Strauss cannons in the return
driven forcefully down to long-off and that's the New Zealand 200 up
cracker! Franklin picks up a length ball and sails it over midwicket
another full toss, on the off side, and that's driven out wide of cover
another low full toss and that's driven out to long-on. Suicidal stuff from the batsmen, attempting a second that was never on and Nixon whips off the bails

inn2.comm: poor start, his foot was well over the line
outside off stump and Strauss watched it pass by
fullish but again a foot or so outside the off stump and Strauss not even sniffing
short of a length, Strauss turned square and the ball squirts edgily into the  gully
more chirrups from the close fielders but Strauss never had to even worry about it as it was so wide
short on off stump and Strauss looks to pull but is so early on it that Franklin has barely let go of it as he swivels
the first run off the bat as Strauss plonks it up to mid-on to steal the strike
wide full toss, steered into the gully where Oram makes a sprawling stop some way to his right. Oram apologises
crazy tip and run ... Strauss drops and calls for one, Taylor races in from cover and had he hit at the bowler's end then Strauss would have been out by some way
super yorker, horrible one to get first ball and he just digs it out
wider and Loye leaves
smack! Too much width, a half volley as well, and Loye rips that through the covers, all along the ground
big shout for leg-before, Loye half forward but the umpire rules it was going down the leg
fullish, leggish, hits him on the pads as he shapes to flick away
full again and a slightly cramped Strauss pushes it to mid-on

the TV commentators spend two balls explaining how bowlers have sussed Strauss and bowl full at his legs to stifle him ... so Franklin promptly bangs one in and he pulls it to the man on the deep square boundary
Loye blocks
angled across Loye who spars at it, causing high levels of excitement in the slips
pushed square and Oram makes a diving stop
full, well driven straight on the off side, right in the groove he so thrives on
pushed out into the off
mistimed drive which bounces and bobbles to cover
short, Strauss sways out of the way of one sent down with real oomph
slightly lazy swish, the ball flies over the slips, never a chance
pushed into the leg side

big shout for caught behind as Loye jabs down on a full toss, everyone terribly enthusiastic, but the umpire rules a bump ball. Fleming walks down to ask if the incident can be referred to the third umpire but it told only if there is doubt whether the ball carried
squirted into the leg side
inswinging half volley, punched into the covers
Strauss forced back to block
once again crisply driven to short extra cover
driven wide of Vettori at mid-off and a single despite a tumbling stop
punched between cover and extra cover, not quite timed but it has enough legs to allow the batsmen to amble back for a second
dropped a few feet into the leg side
wide and left alone
Strauss again misses an attempted pull
deliberately steered over gully
Loye shapes to pull-sweep but edges into his body
short and wide, cut to the man at deep backward cover
Loye back, right into line and watchfully plays into the off

wide half volley angled across the right hander, a rather loose flash and a thick edge is well held at chest height by Fleming at first slip ... Fleming makes a sarcastic appeal to the umpire and who can blame him ...
Bell forced to play from the off, straight and full
tip and run, good communication as that hardly went anywhere into the off side and yet there was never a chance of a run-out
outside off stump and Strauss barely moves
wide, left alone
wide and short for variety
worked off the back foot to point
worked down off the back foot where second slip takes a diving roll to his left. New Zealand are jaunty in the field, matching England's earlier enthusiasm
good pace and bounce there and Bell's forced to defend down off the back foot towards the gully region
driven, slowly, to cover and that rounds off a good maiden
Strauss takes that from leg and works it round off his legs behind square
tidy shot from Strauss, driving that through cover firmly and with good timing and that races away
defended forward this time
oh, Strauss gets a headrush there and flashes over that one which is on a good length, but wide
straight and up there and that's worked off the toes softly into midwicket
right up there, straight and true and there's little doubt that that's out. Full length, Strauss looking to play across the line, and that would have comfortably taken leg stump
rising bouncer, and swings away, Bell does well to jerk his head back out of the way
defended on the front foot this time
nibbled off the back foot into the cover
pushed up there and defended on the front foot
good leave as that one angles across the left hander from over the wicket
straight and worked down off the back foot to cover
left alone outside off stump
angles across the right hander and that's defended on the front foot this time
gone! It went low and just about carried to Fleming at first slip who does well to snap up a tidy catch. England are in trouble now at 31 for 3
defended off the back foot
another dot ball - will this be a wicket maiden?
angles that one across, and Collingwood works it off the back foot to covers
driven slowly to cover
worked into short midwicket
swayed away past the shoulder and Joyce bent away from it
defended off the back foot into the cover
zippy that one - 93.1mph (150kmh) - and the keeper jerked back as he took it
driven off the back foot through cover
worked to point off the back foot
worked across the righthander who left it
kept low and crashed off the inside edge into the pads
swayed away across the righthander
crashed down leg and off the pad
slower ball, picked and worked into the covers
worked into the covers
defended down
left alone outside off
driven straight down the ground and the seagulls are scattered by the relay throw
jabbed down defensively off the back foot
worked off the hips square
angles in at the righthander and it's defended down off the back foot
wide and that's driven easily through cover
defended
defended off the back foot
more defence here
defending seems to be the order of the day
one more defensive shot to finish the over
left alone outside off and that one sways slightly away
defended down off the back foot
on the money and defended
defended off the back foot
stands tall on his back foot and drives the ball to cover but can't puncture the circle
outside off and there's a swing and miss
worked into point
comes down the track to try to blast that over mid-off, misses, and narrowly avoids being stumped
driven softly into cover
defended this time
more defence, this time on the back foot
strays down leg and that's worked off the toes to square
over square leg, but not controlled properly, taking his eyes off the ball and sending it high in the air - on to him much quicker than expected
down leg again, poor delivery, but Joyce does well to turn it very fine indeed off his legs
worked into the covers and the batsman decide to "Wait!"
driven to long-off
worked off the back foot into the covers
driven off the back foot to point
defended down off the back foot
walks over to think about working that to leg, gets bat on it and moves it into short midwicket
strays down leg and the batsman guides that to square
worked off the toes behind square
defended forward
over the wicket at the left hander and that's defended forward
worked off the back foot to point
driven to cover
pushed up there and driven to cover
worked off the back foot into the covers
late cut just away from first slip
worked into the cover
worked to square
bends that down with the slightest of turn back into the left hander and defended
creeps past the outside edge
swept away to the square-leg boundary
defended
driven to cover this time
whips it away fine through fine leg
great shot, taken a few shots down the pitch, and hooked to the boundary in front of midwicket
full bunger, driven out to cover
worked off the hips behind square
comes forward to defend
worked tight into the leg-side
pitches outside off and that turns a touch in at the lefthander who defended into the covers
outside off and that's nibbled down off the back foot
driven to cover off the front foot where it's picked up tidily
driven to mid-on this time
worked down to fine leg
driven to short midwicket
outside off and that's worked off the back foot through the covers
worked off the back foot to point
driven to cover
pushed on the back foot and that's defended down
top edge square but that lands in space
"that's out" cries everyone in the office before the umpire has even got chance to raise his finger. Collingwood on one knee trying to sweep there and that would have gone straight one - great ball
trapped in the crease with no footwork and just swooshes at that - it flies past his outside edge
defended this time
defended into the covers
good bowling again, changing the pace and Flintoff can only defend forward
on leg and that's worked out in front of square for a quick single
driven off the back foot to point
on the money and that's defended into the covers
